_line", "prob": 0.8790735006332397, "span": {"begin": 1942, "end": 1949}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.800416886806488, "span": {"begin": 1961, "end": 1963}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3553"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-1&beta;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9103606939315796, "span": {"begin": 1961, "end": 1971}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3553"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9774526357650757, "span": {"begin": 1986, "end": 1990}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9489073157310486, "span": {"begin": 2015, "end": 2019}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3554"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-1R", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918494820594788, "span": {"begin": 2029, "end": 2034}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.95374596118927, "span": {"begin": 2052, "end": 2056}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3553"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-1&beta;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9857751727104187, "span": {"begin": 2141, "end": 2151}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.934100329875946, "span": {"begin": 2194, "end": 2201}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:920"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CD4+", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9921539425849915, "span": {"begin": 2216, "end": 2220}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3553"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8083745837211609, "span": {"begin": 2241, "end": 2245}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DCs", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8381924033164978, "span": {"begin": 2291, "end": 2294}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7124"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TNF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9845349788665771, "span": {"begin": 2356, "end": 2359}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "allergen-specific T cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.6987355351448059, "span": {"begin": 2375, "end": 2400}}], "text": "RelB deficient mice had an impaired cellular immunity, as observed in contact sensitivity reaction&nbsp;(Weih et al., 1995).  Quite a few NF-kB inhibitors have been reported. MG132, bortezomib, curcumin, DHMEQ(Dehydroxymethylepoxyquinomicin), naringin, sorafenib, genistein and parthenolide are some of representatives&nbsp;(Pordanjani and Hosseinimehr, 2016).  Interferon-&gamma; (IFN-&gamma;) production in response to CMV-infected fibroblasts was reduced under the influence of MG132, a proteosome inhibitor as&nbsp; well as a NF-kB inhibitor,&nbsp; in a dose-dependent manner. A marked reduction was observed at 0.5&thinsp;&mu;M. Likewise, CMV-specific cytotoxicity of CD8(+) T cells was decreased in the presence of MG132&nbsp;(Wang et al., 2011).  In vivo MG132 administration to NC/Nga mice with DNFB-induced dermatitis reduced Th17 cells but maintained the level of Th1 cells, resulting in the alleviation of dermatitis lesions by decreasing both serum IgE hyperproduction and mast cell migration&nbsp;(Ohkusu-Tsukada et al., 2018).  Proteasome inhibitor, bortezomib, potently inhibits the growth of adult T-cell leukemia cells both in vivo and in vitro&nbsp;(Satou et al., 2004). Bortezomib inhibits T-cell function versus infective antigenic stimuli in a dose-dependent manner in vitro&nbsp;(Orciuolo et al., 2007).  Dehydroxymethylepoxyquinomicin (DHMEQ), a novel nuclear factor-kappaB inhibitor, induces selective depletion of alloreactive or phytohaemagglutinin-stimulated peripheral blood mononuclear cells, decreases production of T helper type 1 cytokines, and blocks maturation of dendritic cells&nbsp;(Nishioka et al., 2008).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&n  Regarding the suppression of NF-kB by impaired IL-1 signaling, it was reported that delayed-type hypersensitivity (DTH) responses were significantly suppressed in IL-1&beta;-deficient and IL-1&alpha;/&beta;-deficient mice. Lymph node cells derived from antigen-sensitized IL-1&beta;-deficient and IL-1&alpha;/&beta;-deficient mice&nbsp;and IL-1R type I-deficient mice, exhibited reduced proliferative responses against antigen. These data suggest that IL-1&beta; is necessary for the efficient priming of T cells. In addition, CD4+&nbsp;T cell-derived IL-1 plays an important role in the activation of DCs during the elicitation phase, resulting in the production of TNF, that activate allergen-specific T cells&nbsp;(Nambu et al., 2006).&nbsp;  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:14:16 +0000 2026"}